# Standalone Microservice - AI Assistant Rules

Whenever you are generating, refactoring, or modifying code within this standalone microservice repository, you MUST adhere to the following architectural rules. This ensures perfect continuity with the core IntranetPortal monolith.

## 1. Entity Framework Configurations
- Do NOT clutter the `DbContext.cs` file's `OnModelCreating` method with inline `.ToTable()` or `.HasOne()` declarations.
- **Rule:** Group its Entity configurations inside dedicated folders (e.g., `Data/Configurations/`).
- Create a specific configuration class implementing `IEntityTypeConfiguration<T>` for each Entity.
- The `DbContext` will automatically pick these up via `modelBuilder.ApplyConfigurationsFromAssembly(...)`.

## 2. Backend HTTP API Layer (.NET)
- When crossing the API boundary (Controllers), never expose EF Core Entities directly. Use bounded Data Transfer Objects (DTOs) tailored exactly for the module's REST inputs/outputs.

## 3. Audit Logging Guidelines
- Audit logs MUST be implemented as localized, module-specific tables with strong foreign keys to the parent entities rather than relying on a single generic global audit table in the monolith. This enforces strict modularity and high-performance indexing.

## 4. UI SVG Iconography
- Do NOT install or use 3rd-party React components for icons (e.g. `lucide-react`, `@heroicons/react`).
- Maintain visual consistency by pasting raw, inline `<svg>` elements matching the exact visual style of the main application (e.g. Heroicons, `strokeWidth={2}`).

## 5. Frontend Layouts
- Root wrappers (`layout.tsx`/`page.tsx`) across major Next.js routes within this microservice MUST strictly use `<div className="max-w-7xl mx-auto space-y-8">`.
- Do NOT inject arbitrary native paddings (e.g., `p-8`, `px-4`) or nested structural containers (e.g., `bg-white min-h-[600px]`) into these entry points, so the UI mimics the parent portal perfectly.
